--------------------
If you find yourself repeating the same sequence of prompts across differen=
t sessions, you can have Claude Code save that workflow as a reusable slash=
 command.=20

Meta staff engineer John Kim [demonstrated](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=
=3DmZzhfPle9QU) this by asking Claude to pull articles about iOS from Hacke=
r News and save a summary to his local =E2=80=9C.claude=E2=80=9D directory.=
 Once the task was complete, he simply told Claude:=20

```
Save what we just did into a new skill called fetch-hackernews
```
Claude generated a markdown file in =E2=80=9C.claude/skills/=E2=80=9D that =
contains a system prompt capturing the entire workflow. This file is automa=
tically registered as =E2=80=9C/fetch-hackernews=E2=80=9D command, allowing=
 you to rerun the whole process from scratch. When Kim wanted to add anothe=
r source, he didn't need to manually edit the file, he simply told Claude:=20

```
Extend this fetch-hackernews skill to also pull from Apple developer news
```
Claude updated the skill to incorporate the new source. This concept works =
for any repetitive task: from running test suites to generating changelogs =
or deployment checklists. Just run through the workflow once, ask Claude to=
 save it, and you=E2=80=99ll have a custom slash command ready for future s=
essions.=20


